{"cursor":"3411","size":14,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{| style=\"float: right;\"\n|- {{Infobox philosopher region = Western Philosophy era = Ancient philosophy\n|color = #B0C4DE image = St Euthymius of Athos (Akhtala fresco).JPG caption = A\n|13th-century fresco of Euthymius from the Akhtala monastery name = Euthymius\n|the Athonite (áá¥ááááá ááááááá) birth_date = c. 955 AD death_date = c. 1024 AD\n|school_tradition= main_interests = Theology, Art, Literature, Canon Law\n|influenced = notable_ideas = [[sibrdzne balavarisa]]\n}}\n|-\n|\n|}\n\n'Euthymius the Athonite' ( Ekvtime Atoneli) (ca.955–1028) was a renowned\nGeorgian philosopher and scholar, also known as 'Eufimius the Abasgian' or 'St.\nEuthymius the Georgian'. His feast day in the Orthodox Church is May 13.\n[http://www.synaxarion.gr/gr/sid/3152/sxsaintinfo.aspx á½ á½ÏÎ¹Î¿Ï Îá½Î¸ÏÎ¼Î¹Î¿Ï á½\ná¼Î¸ÏÎ½Î¯ÏÎ·Ï ÎºÏÎ®ÏÎ¿ÏÎ±Ï Ïá¿Ï Î.Î. á¼¸Î²Î®ÏÏÎ½]. 13 ÎÎ±ÎÎ¿Ï. ÎÎÎÎÎ£ Î£Î¥ÎÎÎÎÎ¡ÎÎ£Î¤ÎÎ£.\n\nThe son of Ioane Varaz-vache Chordvaneli and nephew of the great Tornike\nEristavi, Euthymius was taken as a hostage to Constantinople but was later\nreleased and became a monk joining the Great Lavra of Athanasios on Mount Athos.\nHe subsequently became the leader of the Georgian Iviron monastery and emerged\nas one of the finest Eastern Christian theologians and scholars of his age.\nFluent in Georgian, Greek and other languages, he translated many religious\ntreatises and philosophical works. Among his major works was the translation of\nsibrdzne balavarisa (Wisdom of Balahvari), a Christianized version of episodes\nfrom the life of Gautama Buddha that became very popular in Medieval Europe as\nthe story of Barlaam and Josaphat. Of equal importance was Euthymiusâ work to\nprepare Georgian translations of various Greek philosophical, ecclesiastical and\nlegal discourses.\n","linknr":157,"url":"Euthymius_the_Illuminator","recorded":1374764263,"links"